<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
The monospecific 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Geesink, Leiden Bot. Ser. 8: 93" authorityYear="1984" baseAuthorityName="Roxb." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Endosamara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Endosamara racemosa" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Endosamara racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recognised at generic level by 
<bibRefCitation author="Geesink, R" journalOrPublisher="Kew Bulletin" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" refId="B38" refString="Geesink, R, 1984. Scala Milletiarum, a survey of the genera of the Millettieae (Legum. -Pap.) with methodological considerations. Leiden Botanical Series 8." title="Scala Milletiarum, a survey of the genera of the Millettieae (Legum. - Pap.) with methodological considerations. Leiden Botanical Series 8." year="1984">Geesink (1984</bibRefCitation>
: 93) principally by its unique fruits with their seeds forming segregating loments encased in endocarp each with a flat wing, a unique feature within the tribe. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. Geesink, Leiden Bot. Ser. 8: 93" authorityYear="1984" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Endosamara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Endosamara" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Endosamara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has stipules 6-12 mm long (vs. 3-7 mm in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Sigmoidala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sigmoidala" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Sigmoidala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 1-6 mm in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Endl., Gen. Pl. Suppl. 3: 104" authorityYear="1843" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Callerya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Callerya" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Callerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">s.str.</emphasis>
), lacks floral bracteoles, has glabrous ovaries and glabrous standard petals (vs. back of standard pubescent in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Sigmoidala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sigmoidala" order="Fabales" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Sigmoidala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
